commit.message:
Test Python 3.7 instead of 3.3

Seems like Travis doesn't support testing in a Python 3.3 env anymore.

List mlflow to the projects using Gorilla

Thanks @hhoeflin!
Fix formatting
List the unreleased changes
Fix `__weakref__` showing up in the doc
Shorten docstrings for non-public functions
Fix the changelog reference.

Do not use `super(type(self), self)`

The first argument of the function `super` needs to refer to the current
class, not to any possible inheriting class.

Rearrange module imports

These are to be organized in this order:

  - built-in imports.

  - third-party imports.

  - `sys.path` insertions.

  - local imports.

Rework the project's metadata

The goal is to centralize all the metadata in a single place for other
scripts to easily retrieve it.

To keep the source code cleaner, the metadata could have been gathered
in a separate file but, since it can also be useful for the users to
programmatically query such metadata (mostly the `__version__`, really),
it is best to directly expose it from within the main module.
Set the `__all__` attribute
Make use of styling and linting tools
Update the setup file
Insert a '_' for tests on internal functions
Add the '.rst' extension to the changelog
Bump to v0.3.0
Replace `x.__class__` with `type(x)`

Rework how sandbox modules are used in tests

Mostly, it:

  - makes the process more robust (fixed an issue in
    `test_find_patches_2()`).

  - makes it easier to manage the modules to load/unload.

  - adds an underscore prefix to avoid possible name clashes with
    modules from the library.
Use the `tearDown` method
Explicitely define the expected patches
Cover the loading of modules during iteration
Deepcopy all the things
Increase coverage
Get decorator data to support class inheritance
Document attribute types

Make the decorator data interface public

Might be useful for debugging purposes.
Change the default for the 'set_default' parameter
Remove extraneous sort
Fix the settings not being properly inherited

Unleash the horses

Make it possible for the users to add attributes to the `Patch` class.
